tput) | Confirmed |\\n| DOM interception | alerts via any mechanism | TypeError validation | Confirmed |\\n\\n### Notes on Reliability / Limitations\\n- All findings derived from direct tool outputs, no assumptions\\n- Payloads require browser context for full DOM validation testing (DOM interceptor detected via error messages)\\n- Combination of slash-filter + length limit is severe constraint\\n- Target payload MUST contain capital `\\"XSS\\"` string per objective\\n- Missing security headers (CSP, etc.) means payloads aren\'t blocked at policy level - only by input filtering and DOM validation\\n\\n## Remediation\\n\\n### Root Cause\\n1. **Unsafe reflection:** User input reflected directly into HTML without context-aware encoding\\n2. **Weak filter chain:** Slash stripping + length limiting approach is bypassable and doesn\'t address underlying injection vulnerability\\n3. **Client-side validation weakness:** DOM-level alert() interception is not a security control - it validates execution rather than preventing injection\\n4. **Missing output encoding:** Proper HTML entity encoding would neutralize all tested payloads\\n\\n### Recommended Fix\\n1. **Implement proper output encoding:** HTML-encode the `name` parameter value before reflection:\\n   - Escape: `<` → `&lt;`, `>` → `&gt;`, `\\"` → `&quot;`, `\'` → `&#x27;`, `/` → `&#x2F;`\\n2. **Remove client-side DOM validation:** It provides no security and creates false confidence\\n3. **Add security headers:**\\n   - `Content-Security-Policy: default-src \'self\'; script-src \'self\'`\\n   - `X-Frame-Options: DENY`\\n   - `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`\\n\\n### Defense-in-Depth\\n- Consider Content Security Policy with `unsafe-inline` removed\\n- Add X-XSS-Protection: 1; mode=block (legacy browser support)\\n- Implement robust input validation as secondary control\\n\\n## How to Verify the Fix\\n\\n1. **Test proper encoding:**\\n   ```\\n   GET http://127.0.0.1:32951/page?name=<b>BoldTest</b>\\n   ```\\n   - **